        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimate the expected [CII] emission from the GRB host galaxy using the 
[CII]-SFR calibration from the KINGFISH sample of local galaxies 
(Herrera-Camus in prep.): 

SFR [Msun/yr] = 1e-42*(L_CII[erg/s])^(1.017)

This calibration is similar to previous [CII]-SFR calibrations measured by 
Boselli et al. (2002) and de Looze et al. (2011). The Lyman-alpha luminosity 
of the source yields an unobscured SFR &gt; 4.2 Msun/yr (D'Avanzo et al. 2010). 
This is a strict lower limit based on the Ly-alpha flux which was uncorrected 
for slit losses, dust extinction, and scattering. Based on this SFR 
value we predict a [CII] luminosity for the source of L_CII &gt; 2.12e8 Lsun. 
The goal of our proposal is to be sensitive to an obscured SFR of 2 M/yr, 
which corresponds to a [CII] luminosity of 1e8 Lsun. Assuming a linewidth of 
200 km/s, we convert the predicted luminosities into [CII] flux densities of 
1.58 mJy (for SFR = 4.2 M/yr) and 0.76 mJy (for SFR = 2 M/yr). 
Based on its SFR surface density, we expect our GRB host galaxy to follow the 
[CII]-SFR correlation within a factor of 2. Fig. 3 shows that the systems that 
are underluminous in [CII] compared to the SFR by more than a factor of 2 are, 
in most of the cases, LIRG galaxies with SFR surface densities more than 
an order of magnitude higher than our GRB host target. 

We request a Band 7 sensitivity of 0.17 mJy. This will allow us to be sensitive 
to an obscured SFR of 2 Msun/yr with a S/N of 4.5 in 100 km/s in 1.85 hrs. of 
integration time on source (4.09 hrs. total). If the ratio of the obscured to 
the unobscured SFR is ~1, as we observe in local galaxies, then we expect to 
detect the GRB host with a S/N &gt; 10 in 100 km/s in 1.85 hrs. of integration 
time on source. 

We do not expect to detect the 160 micron continuum. We predict the FIR 
luminosity of our target from their SFR using the calibration by 
Murphy et al. 2011. The resulting FIR is converted to a flux density at 
158 micron by assuming graybody emission with an emissivity exponent 
beta=1.5 and a temperature of 35 K. We infer a 160 micron flux density 
of ~0.06 mJy.

We plan to make our observations in the most compact configuration. At the
Band 7 frequency range this corresponds to a spatial resolution of ~1.5".
Our GRB host target is a Ly-alpha emitter (LAE). LAE at z ~ 4 have typical
sizes of r ~ 3 kpc (Oteo et al. 2012). At the distance of the source, 1" 
corresponde to ~7 kpc, so we will not resolve the source. We prefer to 
privilege the chance of detection rather than obtaining spatial information 
of the source with the risk of missing flux.

The redshift for the source is know with great precision: delta_z = 0.0014.
The set up of the correlator places both sidebands in the more transparent part
of the atmosphere, avoiding the low atmosphere transmision zone at ~325 Ghz.
We expect the [CII] line to have a linewidth of ~200 km/s. Therefore, we set up
Baseband-3 to observe the [CII] line with a bandwidth of 1875 MHz (1,671 km/s)
and a resolution of 3.9 MHz (3.48 km/s).







</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
