    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Gamma Ray Bursts (GRB) are very useful tools to identify and explore the most distant galaxies in the universe. At the present time, most of the observations of GRB hosts at high-z has been done in the rest-frame UV and optical wavelengths. This complicates the analysis and the interpretation of the star formation activity due to the unknown geometry and strength of the internal dust extinction. With the proposed observations we will study the obscured star formation activity of the galaxy that hosted the GRB 090205 at z = 4.65 by observing its redshifted [CII] 158 micron emission. This galaxy is a Ly-alpha emitter with one of the highest metallicities measured among the high-z GRB host population (Z &gt; 0.3 Zsun). Based on the [CII] line emission -- a major coolant for the neutral atomic gas -- we will infer the obscured SFR of the GRB host system. This exploration of the properties of a GRB host galaxy using an exciting new probe of its ISM -- unavailable before ALMA -- will make a significant contribution to our understanding of this field of studies. </prp:abstract>
